[2]
Date: Thu 16 May 2002
From: Finerty, John (NCI) <finertyj@mail.nih.gov>

Re: Hepatitis A Virus IgM Antibody Prevalence
---------------------------------------------
The presence of IgM antibody -- as the only immunoglobulin isotype detected
in an assay -- usually means a recent case of infection. However, it has
been demonstrated that pure polysacharride antigens will induce only an IgM
response. Plus low "intensity" chronic infections -- in animal studies --
only produced an IgM response. The issue/opportunity is that we know very
little of the dynamics/mechanisms of the human immune response to
infectious agents. Additional comments [to Dr. Finnerty at <fin@nih.gov>]
are welcomed.

--
John F. Finerty, Ph.D.,Chief
Cellular Immunology & AIDS Lymphoma Section
Cancer Immunology & Hematology Branch
National Cancer Institute, NIH
EPN, Rm. 5060
6130 Executive Boulevard
Rockville, MD 20852
<fin@nih.gov>

