[3]
Thu 16 May 2002
From: Brad Walsh <epibeemie@hotmail.com>

Re: Hepatitis A Virus IgM Antibody Prevalence
---------------------------------------------
In a couple of years of work on viral hepatitis surveillance in north
central Texas for the state health department I can recall seeing only one
Hepatitis A virus IgM positive result that didn't come with very elevated
liver functions attached, out of several thousand submitted. Is Dr.
Rosenberg perhaps confusing this test with the hepatitis A IgG or hepatitis
A virus total antibody tests, which are said (e.g. the Red Book) to be
positive for about 20% of the US population who have no evidence of current
acute viral hepatitis (i.e. presenting a serologic history of remote
previous exposure)?

I know one of the ProMed-mail moderators offers stern caveats to the use of
single serum IgM testing for diagnosing most diseases. Yet it would seem
from my public health surveillance experience that the hepatitis A virus
IgM is among the most reliable IgM tests out there.

The biggest problem I encountered with the IgM test was the occasional slow
converter. Since the titer level for a positive test is set fairly high,
once in awhile you'd have an icteric patient who was highly suspect (e.g.
household contact of a confirmed case) and who would test negative on the
first test. On two of the three occasions I can think of, this was an older
person who might therefore have had a slower-moving immune system. One of
these two was re-tested and was positive. The third was a child that stayed
negative through three tests, but still managed to pass it on to family
members, who did test IgM positive.

--
Brad Walsh, MPH
Parkland Hospital
Dallas
<epibeemie@hotmail.com>

