[4]
Date: Thu 16 May 002
From: Hollinger, Blaine <blaineh@bcm.tmc.edu>

Re: Hepatitis A Virus IgM Antibody Prevalence
---------------------------------------------
Can you clarify what you mean regarding the "addition of hepatitis A virus
IgM antibody to a screening panel for liver disease"? As you know, when a
patient is seen by a physician with what appears to be acute hepatitis,
their serum or plasma is sent to the laboratory to be tested for IgM
anti-HAV if the clinician suspects a recent hepatitis A virus infection.
The physician usually asks for an acute hepatitis panel, but the various
tests are individually run. I am unclear as to what you are describing and
how it could be a factor in the outcome of the test.

Regarding the specificity of the IgM anti-HAV test, I am glad that you said
that "up to" 10 percent of healthy persons will have a positive IgM
anti-HAV test, because the percent is closer to 0 in my experience. Abbott
Laboratories would say that it is <0.1 percent. My estimate is based on
considerable experience testing samples for hepatitis A virus (and other
hepatitis agents), including the development of some of the initial tests
for this virus. Indeed, I can't recall detecting any false-positive
reactions in a properly performed assay nor do I recall being asked to
render an opinion in which the IgM anti-HAV was considered to be falsely
positive. This may partly be due to the fact that the sample is diluted to
about 1:4000 for the assay thereby removing any problematic components such
as rheumatoid factor. Following an acute infection, the IgM anti-HAV
response usually declines to non-detectable levels within 3 to 6 months,
although the antibody can persist for over 200 days in about 14 percent of
patients. The range is reported to be <30 to >420 days. Thus, the detection
of this antibody more precisely indicates a recent infection which could
have occurred more than a year ago. Of course, if the patient is jaundiced
or is acutely ill, the presumption is that this represents acute disease.

Reference:
Hollinger FB, Emerson SU. Hepatitis A Virus. In: Knipe DM, Howley PM, eds.
Fields Virology. Philadelphia: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins, 2001:799-840.

--
F. Blaine Hollinger, M.D.
Professor of Medicine, Virology & Epidemiology
Director, Eugene B. Casey Hepatitis & HIV Research Center
and Diagnostic Laboratory
<blaineh@bcm.tmc.edu>

